    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if the concrete is mostly just handling the squeezing part, what's actually happening inside it during those tension moments? like, is the rebar just sitting there or is there some kind of interaction between the two materials that makes them work as one unit?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interaction between the concrete and the rebar is critical; they are not just sitting side-by-side, but they work together as a single, reinforced unit. When the concrete tries to crack under tension, the rebar, which is embedded within it, engages and resists that pulling force. This bonding, achieved through proper surface preparation and the geometry of the rebar, allows the stress to be transferred from the concrete to the steel. It's a cooperative mechanism where the weak link (concrete in tension) is supported by the strong link (steel in tension).",
      "source": "target",
