    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i get the bonding part. but since the rebar is basically hidden inside the concrete where you cant see it, how do engineers ensure that nothing happens to the integrity of that internal connection over time? like what are the main risks to the bond or the steel itself while it's buried in there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main risks to the integrity of the internal connection involve corrosion and improper detailing. If the concrete cover over the rebar is too thin, moisture and chlorides (like from de-icing salts) can reach the steel, causing it to rust. Rust expands, creating internal pressures that can spall or crack the surrounding concrete, which is a major failure mode. Proper concrete mix design and maintaining adequate concrete cover are essential to protect the steel from the corrosive environment.",
      "source": "target",
